 IT is perfect fitting that the inaugural three-team cricket Solidarity Cup be held on a significant date on the Mzansi calendar, the Nelson Mandela Day. The late elder statesman was all for unity, solidarity, and peace during his presidency.Cricket South Africa (CSA) have announced a revised date for the 3TCricket challenge, now set to take place on 18 July. The three-team match was initially slated in for 27 June, but was moved due to increasing Covid-19 pandemic concerns.But that was before  Sports Minister Nathi Mthethwa gave the green light for teams to return to training.Details of the match haven't changed, with SuperSport Park in Centurion still the host venue. ”It’s very exciting to get live cricket, featuring our top players, back on our TV screens again, ” said CSA Acting CEO Jacques Faul. ”I can't think of a more appropriate day on which to hold this game than the Nelson Mandela Day, when its prime objective is to raise funds for those who have been badly affected by the coronavirus. ”It is still nearly three weeks away and is it also gives our players more time to prepare properly and to minimise the chance of injuries. ”Fans will watch 24 of the country's top cricketers in three teams, led by reknown stars, playing two halves in one match.Kagiso Rabada will lead the Kingfishers, AB de Villiers the Eagles while Quinton de Kock will captain the Kites.The teams:Kingfishers: Kagiso Rabada (c), Chris Morris, Faf du Plessis, Tabraiz Shamsi, Reeza Hendricks, Heinrich Klaasen, Janneman Malan, Glenton Stuurman.Eagles: AB de Villiers (c), Aiden Markram, Lungi Ngidi, Andile Phehlukwayo, Junior Dala, Rassie van der Dussen, Kyle Verreynne, Sisanda Magala.The Kites: Quinton de Kock (c), David Miller, Anrich Nortje, Dwayne Pretorius, Temba Bavuma, Beuran Hendricks, JJ Smuts, Lutho Sipamla. 